ons. With a lively attention to detail, he surveys a sprawling series of debates among rulers, jurists, philosophers, political reformers, writers, and others, who were all engaged in laying the groundwork for our contemporary systems of constitutional governance. Every seemingly new claim about rights turns out to be a variation on a theme, as late medieval notions were subtly repeated and refined to yield the talk of "rights" we recognize today. From the Wars of Religion to the French Declaration of the Rights of Man and of the Citizen to the 1948 Universal Declaration of Human Rights, On the Spirit of Rights is a sweeping tour through centuries of European intellectual history and an essential guide to our ways of thinking about human rights today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aHuman rightsxHistory. 0aHuman rightszFrancexHistory. 0aHuman rightszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aNatural lawxHistory. 4aAmerican Revolution. 4aDeclaration of rights. 4aEnlightenment. 4aFrench Revolution. 4aPhysiocracy. 4ahuman rights. 4anatural constitutionalism. 4anatural law. 4anatural rights. 4asocial naturalism. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226589039423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/doc/cover/9780226589039.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles